    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>EMISSIONS TESTING</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By STEVE STRUNSKY</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Strunsky, Steve</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New Jersey officials, citing possible danger to technicians, consider dropping or delaying part of state vehicle inspection process that would have detected leaks in exhaust systems not found by tailpipe emissions testing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>State officials said last week they may drop or delay part of the state inspection process that was to account for 7 percent of all smog-related emissions reductions. The test, scheduled to be added to the inspection process on July 1, is intended to detect leaks in a car's exhaust system not detected by tailpipe emissions testing. But it would increase inspection and waiting times, and would be a danger to technicians, according to the State Division of Motor Vehicles.</p>
        <p>STEVE STRUNSKY</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
